    "text": "quantum computing and sustainability. As a leader in ethical AI, IBM shapes transparent systems to address global challenges, from healthcare to environmental sustainability. The company also aims to drive innovation through partnerships in space technology, cloud computing and data-driven industries. Industrial Revolution to early 20th century IBM’s roots trace back to Herman Hollerith’s 1896 invention of the tabulating machine, revolutionizing data processing for the 1890 US Census. In 1911, IBM was founded as the Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company, later renamed IBM in 1924. Key innovations followed, such as the 1928 introduction of the 80-column punched card, which became a global data standard. Rise of computing and world conflict IBM introduced the electric accounting machine in 1929. By 1935, it supported Social Security with record-keeping systems. During World War II, IBM aided military operations with punch card technology, and in 1945, it founded the Watson Scientific Computing Lab, marking a significant step toward modern computing. Space Age and Mainframe Revolution Launched in 1964, IBM’s System/360 was a pivotal mainframe computer for businesses and governments. In 1969, IBM systems helped NASA achieve the Apollo moon landing. In 1973, the introduction of the UPC barcode revolutionized retail industries by streamlining inventory management. PC Revolution and digital transformation In 1981, IBM released the IBM PC, revolutionizing personal computing. In 1997, Deep Blue made history by defeating a world chess champion, Garry Kasparov. By the late 1990s, IBM had also developed the world's fastest supercomputer, showcasing its leadership in AI and high-performance computing. Global connectivity and AI IBM shifted toward cloud computing and AI with Watson's 2011 Jeopardy! win, reshaping business optimization and AI-driven solutions. In 2018, IBM and Airbus launched CIMON, the first AI assistant for the International Space Station, expanding its reach into space technology. IBM remains focused on ethical AI systems today. Future of technology and sustainability IBM continues to push the boundaries of AI, quantum computing and sustainability. As a leader in ethical AI, IBM shapes transparent systems to address global challenges, from healthcare to environmental sustainability. The company also aims to drive innovation through partnerships in space technology, cloud computing and data-driven industries. Global impact IBM Impact Report Discover our progress and performance to create a more sustainable, equitable and secure future. IBM Impact Accelerator Explore this initiative, which provides IBM technologies and expertise to nonprofits and governments supporting communities facing environmental and economic stress IBM SkillsBuild Our commitment is to provide 30 million people of all ages with new skills needed for the jobs of tomorrow by 2030. Commitments to the future Future of IBM Future of IBM Future of AI Future of AI Future of work Future of work Future of sustainability Future of sustainability IBM is always on the hunt for what’s next. Learn more about the group of more than 3,000 international scientists and researchers who believe in the power of the scientific method to invent at IBM Research, including leading the charge in quantum computing. Visit the IBM Research lab IBM’s adaptive AI solutions are designed to",
